public_description: NOTE: TO JAKE VALENCIA & CREW4.	Undersized nature of City Auburn Creek street under crossings cause residential flooding.  The City permitted and constructed undercrossing for Auburn Creek were designed for flows that are now large because of a combination of greater Auburn Creek Channelization and the increased development, in the water shed, of impermeable surfaces.  Please have someone observe the Auburn Creek crossings at the following: a.	University Avenue at 51st /Ottilie Street (Number & size of drains undersized);b.	Wightman Street at the Wightman Street park (Auburn Creek channelized and flood plain raised for park);c.	Auburn Creek channel, Southwest of Wightman Street and Park, has an undersized zinc culvert for access to Apartment building.  (The Auburn Creek channel was moved and channelized to allow full development of the Auburn Creek Fox Canyon Flood plain);d.	Flooding of apartment buildings to the East of Wightman Street Park has been caused by inadequate storm water engineering.  The apartment owner annually sand bags the entrance to these apartments and when flood re-dry walls and paints.  I am confident that these apartments have significant mold behind the new dry wall.  (This storm water flood condition is because of the undersized under crossing of storm water from North of University Avenue.  As you know the Wightman Street Park, acquisition was as the result of an inverse condemnation action for flooding.  It was not acquired for flood control or park use. )e.	The Auburn Creek undercrossing, at Fairmount Avenue and Home, is undersized and mis ?designed.  It has flooded out this intersection and adjacent businesses every third year.  (I believe additional flow comes from lack of Auburn Creek maintenance, to the South behind the Goodwill and the Pearl Car Wash, and the fact that sections of Auburn Creek to the North of Fairmount were placed in a box culvert and channelized to eliminate the natural flood plain.  Additionally, the recent installation of free standing solar panel structures, at the Pearl Car Wash, now diverts large volumes of storm water directly into the Auburn Creek instead of the Storm drain system.  This diversion may improve the water quality but it increases the flow concentration and speed.)

Please see attached description and maps. There is a large drain/culvert that allows water to leave the buffer and drain into the bay. We have had issues of dogs going through the pipe to enter the buffer and the actual nesting area. I am requesting that a grate or similar be installed at either end to prevent dogs and other mammals from entering the buffer and nesting site. Below are maps showing the location of the drain pipe.I am a Park Ranger in Mission Bay and I handle the federally mandated California Least Tern nesting program. We have a site at the southwest tip of Fiesta Island within the fenced off dog area. This site is a former sludge storage area and now an off leash dog park. There is a large drain pipe/culvert that is placed within a berm that goes between the nesting buffer zone to a beach that is closed during nesting season from April to September. The issue is that dogs and other predatory mammals use the pipe as a passage way into and out of the nesting area. I have seen this occur and have fielded calls from park users and our contractors about this issue. From April 15 to September 15 of each year, entry into this area is strictly controlled and prohibited as required by federal law. I wanted to see about having a grate or screen installed on the ends of the pipe to prevent dogs and others from entering the area. I have attached a brief description and maps. I would be happy to meet one of your staff at the site to review this issue. My contact info is contained in the attachment. Please let me know if you have questions or need more info.

Hi Ms. Davis ? the City is the correct agency to contact regarding investigation of this issue.  They have the land use authority to investigate and determine whether or not the groundwater is naturally occurring or not.  If the issue requires a solution and it is ground water,  it may require permitting from our agency depending on the source and they type of ownership. Our Regional MS4 Permit requires the City to investigate the complaint in 30 days.   We regulate pollutants in storm water runoff.  You may also file complaints here:https://calepacomplaints.secure.force.com/complaints/ - this is our complaint system and it is forwarded to the correct agency for a response. Please see email dated November 5, 2018 below) Since the 1980's I have had listings for Sale and Rent on Calle Corta. The mineral oil was non-detect for PCB [<1 ppm]. The oil remained on the asphalt parking lot and driveway, in the concrete storm water swale, and in the open stormwater conveyance system for the property and the property behind the Vons & Marshalls shopping center located on Kemper St. and Midway Dr.  An SDG&E HazMat contractor responded to the spill cleanup.  The SDGE HazMat contractor cleaned the parking lot, driveway, and swale with clay-based absorbent.  Then the SDGE HazMat contractor pressure washed the area that had been sprayed with oil. Clean up was conducted on 1/12/26 and 1/13/2026. The oily-absorbent and oily-water was brought back to SDG&E Miramar consolidation site. CMP storm drain from Meadow Lark Dr. to channel at Mission Center Rd. needs to be repaired. It is failing and leaks water out at more than on spot on the hillside. As you can see in the picture it is adjacent to two high voltage transmission structures. The soil type on the hillside is a cobble and when any concentrated amount of water hits the hillside it easily erodes. We don't want to have a tower failure at this site due to the storm drain. It was patched in one area several years ago and the blockage at the bottom was cleared. However, it is leaking in other places uphill from the patch. we have installed BMPs to protect the towers but those are only temporary until the storm drain can be properly repaired. Due to the steepness and soil conditions this might be a prime candidate for relining. I must reiterate, there are four transmission circuits of critical importance to keeping the power on in San Diego. There are two 230kV, one 138kV and one 69kV on those two towers.
street_address: 2255 Meadow Lark Dr, San Diego, CA 92123, USA
